{{Infobox officeholder |image = |name= Dudley Anthony "Butch" Gautreaux |caption= |office=[[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana State Senator from District 21 (effective 2012: Iberia, Lafourche, St. Mary, and Terrebonne parishes)]] |term_start=2000 |term_end=2012 |preceded=John J. Siracusa |succeeded=[[Bret Allain|R. L. "Bret" Allain, II]] |office2=[[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana State Representative from District 51 (then Assumption, St. Mary, and Terrebonne parishes)]] |term_start2=1996 |term_end2=2000 |preceded2=John J. Siracusa |succeeded2=[[Carla Blanchard Dartez]] |birth_date= {{birth date and age|1947|12|21}} |spouse= Marilyn Mire Gautreaux |children= |party= [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] |occupation= [[Business]]man |religion= [[Roman Catholic]] |alma_mater= [[Nicholls State University]] |branch=[[United States Navy]] |footnotes= }}
'''Dudley Anthony Gautreaux''', known as '''Butch Gautreaux''' (born December 21, 1947), is a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] former member of the [[Louisiana State Senate]] from [[Morgan City, Louisiana|Morgan City]], [[Louisiana]]. From 2000 to 2012, he represented Senate District 21. In 2012, the reconfigured district incorporated mostly [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] portions of [[Iberia Parish, Louisiana|Iberia]], [[Lafourche Parish, Louisiana|Lafourche]], [[St. Mary Parish, Louisiana|St. Mary]], and [[Terrebonne Parish, Louisiana|Lafourche]] parishes.<ref name=returns/>
Gautreaux won his last election to the Senate in 2007, when he defeated the Republican Clayton D. Diaz, 25,348 (71 percent) to 10,372 (29 percent). At that time the district also included two precincts in [[St. Martin Parish, Louisiana|St. Martin Parish]], since removed from the reconfiguration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/10202007/10202007_Legislative.html|title=Louisiana primary election returns, October 20, 2007|publisher=staticresults.scs.la.gov|accessdate=October 24, 2011}}</ref>
From 1996 to 2000, Gautreaux was a member of the [[Louisiana House of Representatives]] from District 51 but vacated the post after the single term to run for the Senate.<ref>[http://ballotpedia.org/wiki/index.php/Butch_Gautreaux Gautreaux on Ballotpedia] (accessed 2010 October 8).</ref> In the 1995 general election, Gautreaux defeated the Democrat-turned-Republican [[Joe Harrison (Louisiana politician)|Joe Harrison]], 8,457 votes (69 percent) to 3,809 ballots (31 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/11181995/11181995_Legislative.html|title=Louisiana general election returns, November 18, 1995|publisher=staticresults.sos.la.gov|accessdate=October 24, 2011}}</ref> Harrison was subsequently elected in 2007 to House District 51 and still holds the seat.
== Background == Gautreaux attended [[Nicholls State University]] in [[Thibodaux, Louisiana|Thibodaux]], Louisiana. He served from 1967 to 1972 in the [[United States Navy]]. He is active in [[Rotary International]], having been secretary of the Morgan City chapter. Gautreaux has served as vice president of marketing for Marsianin Industrial Contractors [[Limited liability company|LLC]] in Morgan City and [[Administration (business)|administrator]] for Arabie Trucking Services LLC in Thibodaux.<ref>[http://senate.legis.state.la.us/Gautreaux/biography.asp Gautreaux‚Äôs bio in the Louisiana Senate]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (accessed 2010 October 8).</ref>
== Race for lieutenant governor == Gautreaux sought the [[lieutenant governor]]ship of Louisiana in a 2010 [[by-election|special election]] occasioned by the resignation of incumbent [[Mitch Landrieu]] when Landrieu became [[mayor of New Orleans]]. In a field of eight candidates Gautreaux, who had the official endorsement of the Louisiana [[AFL-CIO]],<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.bayoubuzz.com/buzz/latest-buzz/79226-louisiana-lt-governors-race-dardenne-vs-fayard-is-gender-party-region-showdown |newspaper = BayouBuzz News |first = Christopher |last = Tidmore |title = Louisiana Lt. Governor's Race: Dardenne vs. Fayard Is Gender, Party, Region Showdown |date = 2010-10-11 |accessdate = 2010-10-17 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110928015923/http://www.bayoubuzz.com/buzz/latest-buzz/79226-louisiana-lt-governors-race-dardenne-vs-fayard-is-gender-party-region-showdown |archivedate = 2011-09-28 |df = }} </ref> polled 4 percent of the vote. He then endorsed fellow Democrat [[Caroline Fayard]] in the [[runoff election|runoff]] against the frontrunner, the Republican [[Jay Dardenne]], a former State Senate colleague of Gautreaux's.<ref>{{cite news |first = Ed |last = Anderson |url = http://www.nola.com/news/t-p/capital/index.ssf?/base/news-8/128651950998280.xml&coll=1 |title = Dardenne, Fayard garner ex-rivals' endorsements: Two left in race for lieutenant governor |newspaper = Times-Picayune |issue = Saint Tammany Edition |date = 2010-10-08 |page = A3 |accessdate = 2010-10-08 |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130104074600/http://www.nola.com/news/t-p/capital/index.ssf?/base/news-8/128651950998280.xml&coll=1# |archive-date = 2013-01-04 |dead-url = yes |df = }}</ref> Dardenne won a full term as lieutenant governor in the [[nonpartisan blanket primary]] held on October 22, 2011.
Gautreaux was term-limited in the state Senate and ineligible to run in the October 22 primary. His successor is Republican [[Bret Allain|R. L. "Bret" Allain, II]], who received 14,618 votes (51.4 percent) in the contest with another Republican, Darrin Guidry, who polled 13,846 votes (48.6 percent). No Democrat sought Gautreaux's seat in the revised district.<ref name=returns>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/10222011/10222011_Legislative.html|title=Louisiana primary election returns, October 22, 2011|publisher=staticresults.sos.la.gov|accessdate=October 24, 2011}}</ref>
== Personal life == Gautreaux and his wife, the former Marilyn Mire, are [[Roman Catholic]].<ref>See [http://www.peoplesearch.com/PeopleSearchResults.aspx?firstname=dudley&lastname=gautreaux&statepicked=LA Gautreaux on Peoplesearch] (accessed 2010 October 8).</ref>
