'''Charles Chabot''' ([[baptism|baptised]] 19 March 1815 ‚Äì 15 October 1882) was an English [[graphology|graphologist]] who, as part of the firm of '''Netherclift, Chabot and Matheson''',<ref>{{ cite book | title=The Roupells of Lambeth | author=Harris, J. | year=2001 | location=London | publisher=The Streatham Society | isbn=1-873520-37-9 | pages=95, 124 }}</ref> was an early practitioner of [[questioned document examination]].
Chabot was born [[Battersea]], the son of Charles, a [[lithographer]], and Amy ''n√©e'' Pearson, a couple of [[Hugenot]] descent.<ref name="ODNB">Henderson (2004)</ref>
Beginning as a lithographer, he developed as an expert in [[handwriting]] and became sought after as an [[expert witness]] in a variety of famous [[trial (law)|trial]]s including the [[Roupell case]] and the [[Tichborne Case]].<ref name="ODNB"/>
In 1871, Chabot became involved in establishing the ''[[identity of Junius]]'' and concluded that he was Sir [[Philip Francis (English politician)|Philip Francis]].<ref name="ODNB"/><ref>Chabot (1871)</ref>
Chabot married Sarah ''n√©e'' Nichols in 1842 and the couple parented at least one son, Charles. Chabot died at home in London.<ref name="ODNB"/> and was buried at the [[West Norwood Cemetery|South Metropolitan Cemetery at West Norwood]]
