{{Infobox Officeholder |name = Dismas Nsengiyaremye |image = |office = 3rd [[Prime Minister of Rwanda]] |term_start = 2 April 1992 |term_end = 18 July 1993 |predecessor = [[Sylvestre Nsanzimana]] |successor = [[Agathe Uwilingiyimana]] |office2 = |term_start2 = |term_end2 = |birth_date = 1945 |birth_place = Rwanda |death_date = |death_place = |party = |spouse = |profession = |religion = }} '''Dismas Nsengiyaremye''' (born 1945) served as [[Prime Minister of Rwanda|Prime Minister]] of [[Rwanda]] from 2 April 1992 to 18 July 1993.
A native of [[Gitarama]], he was a member of the [[Republican Democratic Movement]] and was appointed prime minister following an agreement between President [[Juv√©nal Habyarimana]] and the political opposition. During his term, he appointed [[Agathe Uwilingiyimana]] to the Ministry of Education, though she later succeeded him as prime minister.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hill |first=Kevin A. |chapter=Agathe Uwilingiyimana |editor1-first=Rebecca Mae |editor1-last=Salokar |editor2-first=Mary L. |editor2-last=Volcansek |title=Women and the Law: A Bio-Bibliographical Sourcebook |location=Westport, CT |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |pages=323‚Äì8 |year=1996 |edition=ill. |isbn=978-0-313-29410-5 }}</ref>
When it was revealed in February 1993 that the [[Rwandan Defence Forces|army]] was compiling lists of alleged "accomplices" of the [[Rwandan Patriotic Front]], Nsengiyaremye protested against what he called a "witch hunt".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Des Forges|first1=Alison|authorlink=Alison Des Forges|title=Leave None to Tell the Story: Genocide in Rwanda ‚Äì Choosing War ‚Üí He Who Wishes for Peace Prepares for War |date=March 1999|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|location=New York|isbn=1-56432-171-1|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/reports/1999/rwanda/Geno1-3-11.htm}}</ref> Nsengiyaremye fled to Europe not long after he was replaced as prime minister in 1993, citing threats to his life.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Des Forges|first1=Alison|authorlink=Alison Des Forges|title=Leave None to Tell the Story: Genocide in Rwanda ‚Äì Choosing War ‚Üí Splitting the Opposition |date=March 1999|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|location=New York|isbn=1-56432-171-1|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/reports/1999/rwanda/Geno1-3-11.htm}}</ref> He currently lives in exile in Belgium.<ref>{{cite book |last=Twagilimana |first=Aimable |date=6 November 2015 |title=Historical Dictionary of Rwanda |url=https://books.google.com.my/books?id=9E6xCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA172&lpg=PA172&dq=dismas+nsengiyaremye+dictionary&source=bl&ots=UxYRVC-fEK&sig=iz86rPpo_9VsSCERjSPO1DOprgM&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=dismas%20nsengiyaremye%20dictionary&f=false |location= |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |page=172 |isbn=9781442255913 |author-link= }}</ref>
